bridge Wells district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary's Church, Frittenden, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1395–Aft 1462":"1395–after 1462","1395–1462":"1395–1462","1395–1455":"1395–1455","1417–1481":"1417–1481","1372–1420":"1372–1420","1375–Female":"1375–Deceased","22 May 1455":"22 May 1455","Aft 1462":"after 1462","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1462":"1462","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1481":"1481","1417":"1417","1416":"1416",", , Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Saint Mary's Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Willesborough, Ashford district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Willesborough, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Frittenden, Kent, England":"Frittenden, Kent, England","Saint Mary's Church, Frittenden, Tunbridge Wells district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary's Church, Frittenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Webb","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a weaver, from early Middle English <i>webbe</i> (Old English <i>webba</i> (masculine) or <i>webbe</i> (feminine), probably used of both male and female weavers). This word survived into Middle English long enough to give rise to the surname, but was already obsolescent as an agent noun; hence the secondary forms with the agent suffixes <i>-er</i> and <i>-ster</i> (see   Webster  ,   Webber   and compare   Weaver  ).","Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish (Ashkenazic) surnames, cognates of 1, including   Weber   and <b>Weberman</b>.","History: Richard Webb, a Lowland Scot, was an admitted freeman of Boston in 1632, and in 1635 was one of the first settlers of Hartford, CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Webster","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a weaver, from Middle English <i>webbester</i> ‘weaver’ (Old English <i>webbestre</i> ‘female weaver’). By the time of surname formation, the gender distinction of the <i>-stre</i> suffix had almost completely disappeared. Compare   Webb  ,   Webber  , and   Weaver  .","History: The name Webster was brought to North America from England independently by several different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. One John Webster settled in Ipswich, MA, in 1635; another John Webster (died 1661), ancestor of the lexicographer Noah Webster, emigrated to Cambridge, MA, <i>c.</i> 1631 and later became one of the founders of the colony of CT, of which he was appointed governor in 1656. Daniel Webster (1782–1852), politician and orator, was born in Salisbury, NH, a descendant of Thomas Webster, a prominent 17th-century citizen of Ipswich, MA, whose family had settled there around 1635, while he was still a child."]},{"name":"Web","meanings":["English: variant of   Webb  ."]},{"name":"Webber","meanings":["English (Devon and Somerset): occupational name for a weaver, from Middle English <i>webber</i>, an agent derivative of   Webb  .","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Weber   ‘weaver’."]},{"name":"Webbe","meanings":["English: variant of   Webb  ."]}]},{"name":"Joanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Johanne","meanings":["and Norwegian feminine form of   Johan ."]},{"name":"Joann","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":60,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joanne Webb was born in 1395, in Frittenden, Kent, England, her father, John Webb, was 23 and her mother, Joan White, was 20. She married Thomas Masters I in 1416, in St Mary's Church, Frittenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1462, in her hometown, and was buried in Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England."},"et":{"1395–Aft 1462":"1395–pärast 1462","1395–1462":"1395–1462","1395–1455":"1395–1455","1417–1481":"1417–1481","1372–1420":"1372–1420","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","22 May 1455":"22. mai 1455","Aft 1462":"pärast 1462","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1462":"1462","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1481":"1481","1417":"1417","1416":"1416",", , Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Mary's Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Willesborough, Ashford district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Willesborough, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Frittenden, Kent, England":"Frittenden, Kent, England","Saint Mary's Church, Frittenden, Tunbridge Wells district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary's Church, Frittenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1395–Aft 1462":"1395–1462 jälkeen","1395–1462":"1395–1462","1395–1455":"1395–1455","1417–1481":"1417–1481","1372–1